    <url>/2020/10/24/sylow-theorems/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<h1 id="Sylow-Theorems"><a href="#Sylow-Theorems" class="headerlink" title="Sylow Theorems"></a>Sylow Theorems</h1><blockquote>
<p>Too much to learn</p>
</blockquote>
<h2 id="Lemmas-for-Sylow-Theorems"><a href="#Lemmas-for-Sylow-Theorems" class="headerlink" title="Lemmas for Sylow Theorems"></a>Lemmas for Sylow Theorems</h2><p><strong>Define 1 <em>p-Group</em></strong>  Let $p$ a prime number, if the <code>order</code> of Group <code>G</code> is $p^{k}, k&gt; 0$, then we called <code>G</code> $p-group$.</p>
<p>All we discussion is based on the $p-group$.</p>
<p><strong>Lemma 1</strong> Let a $p-group$ acting on set $X$, the order of $X$ equals to $n$, which written as $|X| = n$, we have result listed below:</p>
<ol>
<li>$t \equiv n\mod p$, in the equation, $t = \left |\{x | x \in X, g(x) = x, \forall g\in G\}\right|$;</li>
<li>When $(n,p) = 1$, then $t \geq 1$, and there are some Fixed points in $X$;</li>
<li>The center of <code>G</code> $C(G) \neq \lbrace e \rbrace$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>proof</strong> </p>
]]></content>
